SIMPLE: expedient
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Expedient
<hw>Ex*pe"di*ent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>expediens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>expedire</ets>
to be expedient, release, extricate: cf. F. <ets>exp⟦eacute⟧dient</ets>.
See <er>Expedite</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Hastening or forward;
hence, tending to further or promote a proposed object; fit or proper
under the circumstances; conducive to self-interest; desirable;
advisable; advantageous; -- sometimes contradistinguished from
<contr>right</contr> or <contr>principled</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is <qex>expedient</qex> for you that I go away.</q>
<rj><qau>John xvi. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing but the right can ever be <qex>expedient</qex>, since that
can never be true expediency which would sacrifice a greater good to a
less.</q> <rj><qau>Whately.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Quick; expeditious.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His marches are <qex>expedient</qex> to this town.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Expedient</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Expedient
<hw>Ex*pe"di*ent</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which serves
to promote or advance; suitable means to accomplish an end.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What sure <qex>expedient</qex> than shall Juno find,⟦br⟧
To calm her fears and ease her boding mind?</q>
<rj><qau>Philips.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Means devised in an exigency; shift.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Shift; contrivance; resource;
substitute.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Expediential</ent>⟦br⟧
